🛰️ LTI 3.0 — Latent Trajectory Interpreter

Codename: Little Saturn Black Box
Tagline: From prompt → trajectory → output, fully observable.

⸻

Overview

LTI 3.0 (Latent Trajectory Interpreter) is an observability and reconstruction system for prompt-response dynamics in language models.

It treats prompts as field-generating objects that open structured continuation spaces in semantic space, then tracks how a response:
	•	selects a trajectory
	•	acquires lock into an attractor basin
	•	maintains coherence under constraints
	•	collapses alternative branches
	•	produces a final structured output

LTI turns opaque generation into an inspectable trajectory system.

⸻

Core Idea

A prompt is not just a question.
It is a trajectory generator.

It defines:
	•	a semantic field
	•	a continuation manifold
	•	multiple possible trajectories
	•	constraint geometry
	•	attractor basins
	•	a lock window where commitment occurs

A response is a path through that field.

⸻

Key Concepts

Prompt Signature

Structured representation of a prompt:
	•	abstraction level
	•	ambiguity
	•	domain anchors
	•	epistemic posture
	•	output constraints
	•	latent question hypotheses

⸻

Generative Affordance

How many coherent futures a prompt allows.

Affordance ≈ entropy of valid continuations under meaningful constraints

High affordance:
	•	many valid directions
	•	but still guided

⸻

Trajectory

A path through semantic space during generation.

⸻

Attractor Basin

A stable response mode:
	•	explanation
	•	synthesis
	•	critique
	•	formalization
	•	narrative
	•	procedural

Once entered, generation tends to stay inside it.

⸻

Lock Event

The point where the response commits to a trajectory.

Typically occurs early (first 1–3 sentences).

⸻

Ghost Branch

A near-selected trajectory that didn’t win but still influences the final answer.

⸻

Constraint Bus

All forces shaping generation:
	•	truthfulness
	•	coherence
	•	style
	•	user-fit
	•	safety
	•	clarity
	•	completeness

⸻

Distortion

Information lost or flattened when one trajectory is chosen over others.

